Histogram of Users’ Birthdays

Notes:

#install.packages('ggplot2')
library(ggplot2)

qplot(x = dob_day, data = pf) +
    scale_x_discrete(breaks = 1:31)

# Get other themes
#install.packages('ggthemes', dependencies = TRUE)
library(ggthemes) 
theme_set(theme_minimal(18))

ggplot(aes(x = dob_day), data = pf) +
    geom_histogram() +
    scale_x_discrete(breaks = 1:31)

What are some things that you notice about this histogram?

Response: There is a disproportionately high number of 1’s in the dataset.

Response: I don’t use Facebook.

How many of your friends do you think saw that post?

Think about what percent of your friends on Facebook see any posts or comments that you make in a month. What percent do you think that is?

Omitting NA Values

Notes:

  • NA is an encoding for missing values
ggplot(subset(pf, !is.na(gender)), aes(x = friend_count)) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 25, fill = "darkred", color = "black") +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000), breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) +
    facet_wrap(~ gender)

What’s the difference between the median friend count for women and men?

Why would the median be a better measure than the mean?

Tenure

Notes:

ggplot(aes(x = tenure), data = pf) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 30, color = 'black', fill = '#099DD9')

How would you create a histogram of tenure by year?

ggplot(aes(x = tenure / 365), data = pf) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 8), breaks = seq(0, 8, 1)) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.25, color = 'black', fill = '#F79420') +
    xlab("Years of tenure") +
    ylab("Number of users")

Labeling Plots

Notes:

  • The plots should speak for themselves
ggplot(aes(x = tenure / 365), data = pf) +

    ylab("Number of users in sample") +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 8), breaks = seq(0, 8, 1)) +

## Loading required package: grid
p1 <- ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) +
    xlab("Friend count") +
    ylab("Number of users in sample") +
    geom_histogram(color = 'black', fill = '#5760AB')
p2 <- p1 + scale_x_log10()
p3 <- p1 + scale_x_sqrt()

grid.arrange(p1, p2, p3, ncol = 1)

Add a Scaling Layer

Notes:

  • scales can be added to existing plots(DRY)
  • be careful with the axis names when adding scales
countScale <- ggplot(aes(x = friend_count), data = pf) +
    geom_histogram() +
    scale_x_log10()

logScale <- qplot(x = log10(friend_count), data = pf)

grid.arrange(countScale, logScale, ncol = 2)

Frequency Polygons

qplot(x = friend_count, data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)), binwidth = 10) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000), breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) +
    facet_wrap(~ gender)

qplot(x = friend_count, y = ..count../sum(..count..),
      data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)),
      xlab = "Friend Count",
      ylab = "Proportion of Users with that friend count",
      geom = "freqpoly", binwidth = 10, color = gender) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000), breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50))

Notes:

  • the ticks on the log scale are from the normal plot
ggplot(aes(x = www_likes), data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +

    geom_freqpoly(aes(color = gender)) +
    scale_x_log10() +

    ylab('Count of users with that like count')

    scale_x_continuous()+
    xlab('Likes Count') +
    ylab('Count of users with that like count')

    scale_x_continuous() +
    xlab('Likes Count') +
    ylab('Percentage of users with that like count')

Adjust the code to focus on users who have friend counts between 0 and 1000.

ggplot(subset(pf, !is.na(gender)), aes(x = gender, y = friend_count)) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000))
## Warning in loop_apply(n, do.ply): Removed 2949 rows containing non-finite

# scale_y_continuous removes data points from calculations; use coord_cartesian instead
ggplot(subset(pf, !is.na(gender)), aes(x = gender, y = friend_count)) +
    geom_boxplot() +
    coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1000))

Getting Logical

Notes:

summary(pf$mobile_likes)

pf$mobile_check_in <- ifelse(pf$mobile_likes > 0, 1, 0)
